  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Atrial fibrillation (AF) is prevalent in patients with sick sinus syndrome (SSS) and
      associated with an increased risk of stroke and death. Within the first two years after
      pacemaker implantation almost half of the patients are diagnosed with AF. Studies have
      indicated that an increased amount of stimulation from the pacemaker in the atria is
      associated with an increased amount of AF.

      The aim of the present study is to test the hypothesis that a reduction of stimulation from
      the pacemaker in the atria, and reducing the minimal heart rate, increases the time to AF.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
